Response to reviewers

DYRESM aeration revisited:

Figure 1. A primary critique of the paper was my configuration of the DYRESM aeration. I have rerun the model with the recommended line source diffusor configuration. Increasing the number of ports makes a large difference in the performance of the aerator. Above are a series of model runs where RMSE of the lake temperature range varies with flow rate while the number of plume sources (ports) are held constant. Within each figure pannel, two vertical lines denote the GELI airflow (left most line) and the optimized aeration airflow (right). This result indicates the GELI performed marginally better than aeration

Figure 6 revised:

Figure 2. Another major critique was that I had estimated mechanical efficiency during the period of mixing by averaging with negative values set to zero. I have replotted Figure 6 and calculated average mechanical efficiencies of 2012 and 2013 to be 1.801+-0.0075 and 2.293+-0.023, respectively. These values are in general agreement efficiencies reported by aeration projects, and accord with the new DYRESM results (above).

Dissolved Oxygen at 18 m:

Figure 3. Reviewers wanted to see dissolved oxygen data. Dissolved oxygen at 18 m was depleted more rapidly during mixing but never reached late summer lows of non-mixed years. Disolved Oxygen improved substantially after turnover in mixing years (September - December).

Proportion of lake < 2 mg/L O2:

Figure 4. The proportion of Crystal Lake that was below a dissolved oxygen concentration of 2 mg/L was less in mixed years. Average proportion below 2 mg/L during the experiment was: 2011 = 0.14, 2012 = 0.08, 2013 = 0.06, 2014 = 0.29.
